# CombatMode Lua Safety

Apply these guardrails for all Lua changes in this addon.

## Combat lockdown and secure flow

- Never perform protected/forbidden UI actions in combat unless the API is explicitly combat-safe.
- Guard protected paths with `InCombatLockdown()` and defer changes until safe when needed.
- Keep secure action setup deterministic; avoid dynamic attribute churn during combat.
- Prefer existing secure patterns already used by the addon (`SecureActionButtonTemplate`, macrotext attributes, override bindings).

## Taint-avoidance practices

- Do not replace Blizzard globals/hooks unless required; prefer safe hooks and local wrappers.
- Avoid leaking temporary globals; keep new helpers/functions `local` unless they must be exported.
- Minimize frame script churn in hot paths (`OnUpdate`, high-frequency events).
- Keep binding and frame ownership clear to avoid hidden cross-module side effects.

## CVar and state hygiene

- Read and write CVars through the module that owns targeting/reticle behavior.
- Only change CVars that are part of explicit feature behavior; avoid unrelated CVar writes.
- When changing runtime state (mouselook, targeting, overrides), keep enable/disable symmetry and cleanup paths.

## Defensive Lua style

- Validate inputs from events/settings before acting (nil/type checks on external data).
- Use early returns for invalid state to keep flow clear and reduce taint-prone branching.
- Reuse existing constants/default tables rather than duplicating magic strings/numbers.
- Keep per-frame work small; avoid expensive table churn in frequently-called code.

## Config and persistence safety

- New settings must have sane defaults and a clear DB scope (`global` vs `char`).
- Keep option handlers side-effect aware: UI toggles should map directly to a feature apply/refresh function.
- Avoid hidden migrations in random modules; keep data-shape transitions explicit and centralized.
